issue.body:
In the future it may be good to allow to export these choices to allow onnxruntime-gpu use exact same conv params and not have surprising slow-downs (https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/6744)

Full implementation of this feature may require some standard for exchanging these parameters between frameworks, maybe the ONNX format could include these in some metadata section

In the meanwhile, I'll check if [cudnn logging](https://docs.nvidia.com/deeplearning/cudnn/developer-guide/index.html#api-logging) is useful for displaying the decided conv params choice

cc @csarofeen @ptrblck @xwang233 @houseroad @spandantiwari @lara-hdr @BowenBao @neginraoof @SplitInfinity

body: Can you share the specific model and test inputs you're using?
We're about to publish a full repro (a single-layer Conv1d model). So far we see that PyTorch lays out inputs as BC1W and ONNXRT as BCH1, not sure if it affects algorithm choice

@faxu Full investigation at https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/7212

Forcing DEFAULT algorithm eliminates 4x slowdowns. Still, ONNXRT seems to have bugs around working with `cudnnFindConvolutionForwardAlgorithmEx`.

This PR https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/7227 might have address the issue. 
We need to set the cudnnSetConvolutionMathType properly before doing the algo search. 
see changes in conv.cc CudnnConvolutionDescriptor::Set() 

I will implement the algorithm search for ConvGrad in the next PR. Will look at this problem all together. 

Please let me know if this fix has address the issue.

Even if it is, perf must be tested at least against PyTorch for various conv shapes / inputs... It would be good if the user could easily rerun the benchmark on their machine. Conv1d is a basic scenario that should not have 4x slowdown surprises...
Are there some nightly binaries available that we could install with pip? If yes, we could test it
And in any case, it would be good to have public results of some benchmarks and micro-benchmarks
@SherlockNoMad Does the nightly build `ort-gpu-nightly 1.7.0.dev202104061` (released 4 hours ago) from https://test.pypi.org/project/ort-gpu-nightly/ contain these fixes? Thanks!
Maybe fixed in https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/7348, but we're still testing the nightly
